Hi /b/

I have a bit of an odd scenario I could use advice on.
I’ve been depressed for years. I just turned 28 last Monday and I’ve accomplished little in my life. Im still at home because I’ve been unable to be consistently employed, and I’ve always failed when I try to make a life for myself.
Out of desperation between suicide and a life change, I applied to a university in Japan as a meme and somehow got accepted. Classes start in January and I fully budgeted the cost of life there. The monthly expenses not counting food are as follows:

Phone- $35
internet- $51
Trains - $120
Rent -$604
Loan - $141(I will need to take a loan to cover the difference i owe on my car)

I found a small but manageable apartment in shinjuku. It’s a little old and you hear noise from other remnants and fire trucks, but it’s a place of my own and that’s more than the bedroom I have currently.(pic related)

To get a feel for it, I went there this weekend. In fact as I write this I’m on the plane back to America. I had never left the country in my life, never left the state in my life, and I went there all alone on a 3 day weekend trip without telling anyone.
I instantly felt at home, the train system made sense to me, I had no issues getting where I needed to be, and I felt oddly comfortable even with the apartment’s shortcomings. I intentionally did no touristy things. I traveled to places I would for business and school, and back to my apartment, I shopped for basics like toilet paper and tooth paste at a local store nearby, and ate simple foods from 7 Eleven and the like. Really trying to simulate a day to day life instead of a vacation. Shockingly, my depression feels cured, I’m not even down in myself anymore.

I do feel like I can live there happily, but I don’t know if I’m capable of it. I’ve never been able to hold a job, and I failed at school last time I tried. And This will require a $20k student loan. Is this a bad move?
